#: src/pages/CastPage.tsx:134
msgid "A device id is required"
msgstr "A device id is required"

#: src/pages/docs/DevicesHelpPage.tsx:140
msgid "A device's streams become ordinary managed Sources, and its decode slots become ordinary managed Outputs, each carrying a <0>device_ref</0> annotation in its body. The engine's ingest and serving paths are untouched — the binding only tells the driver which device the resource belongs to (and blocks deleting the device while something still references it). Where a vendor does not document a stream URL, the UI flags the candidate as unverified and you supply the URL yourself — it is never silently guessed."
msgstr "A device's streams become ordinary managed Sources, and its decode slots become ordinary managed Outputs, each carrying a <0>device_ref</0> annotation in its body. The engine's ingest and serving paths are untouched — the binding only tells the driver which device the resource belongs to (and blocks deleting the device while something still references it). Where a vendor does not document a stream URL, the UI flags the candidate as unverified and you supply the URL yourself — it is never silently guessed."

#: src/pages/docs/DevicesAdoptHelpPage.tsx:29
msgid "A discovery scan browses the network (mDNS/DNS-SD) for a bounded few seconds and lists what answered. Anything on the network can answer a broadcast, so the results are an untrusted inventory of hints: they are not devices, they carry no credentials, and Multiview never adopts them automatically. Every adoption is an explicit operator confirmation — the row's Adopt button only prefills the dialog; nothing exists until you confirm it."
msgstr "A discovery scan browses the network (mDNS/DNS-SD) for a bounded few seconds and lists what answered. Anything on the network can answer a broadcast, so the results are an untrusted inventory of hints: they are not devices, they carry no credentials, and Multiview never adopts them automatically. Every adoption is an explicit operator confirmation — the row's Adopt button only prefills the dialog; nothing exists until you confirm it."

#: src/pages/docs/DisplayNodesHelpPage.tsx:28
msgid "A display node is a single-board computer or spare PC running Multiview's node software, driving one or more physical displays. Nodes are adopted as managed devices with the <0>displaynode</0> driver and present the program, a declared output, or one head of a video wall. Because the node software is ours end-to-end, display nodes reach the frame-accurate sync tier — every head of a wall shows the same frame index."
msgstr "A display node is a single-board computer or spare PC running Multiview's node software, driving one or more physical displays. Nodes are adopted as managed devices with the <0>displaynode</0> driver and present the program, a declared output, or one head of a video wall. Because the node software is ours end-to-end, display nodes reach the frame-accurate sync tier — every head of a wall shows the same frame index."

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/TransportsPage.tsx:345
msgid "A feed crossing the internet: SRT (tune the latency window to the link)."
msgstr "A feed crossing the internet: SRT (tune the latency window to the link)."

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/TransportsPage.tsx:228
msgid "A file source plays media from disk, paced to real time so it behaves like a live feed on the wall (and can loop). Synthetic sources — color bars, solid fills, and a ticking clock — are generated in-process with no network or decode at all. They are ideal for layout work, burn-in tests, and proving the output path end to end before any real feed is connected."
msgstr "A file source plays media from disk, paced to real time so it behaves like a live feed on the wall (and can loop). Synthetic sources — color bars, solid fills, and a ticking clock — are generated in-process with no network or decode at all. They are ideal for layout work, burn-in tests, and proving the output path end to end before any real feed is connected."

#: src/layout/components/GridLayoutEditor.tsx:288
msgid "A grid layout places cells by named areas on column/row tracks — resize whole rows and columns at once, with even gaps."
msgstr "A grid layout places cells by named areas on column/row tracks — resize whole rows and columns at once, with even gaps."

#: src/pages/docs/FeaturesPage.tsx:27
msgid "A layout decides where every tile sits on the canvas. Use a factory preset (such as 2x2 or 1+5), a CSS-grid with named areas and fractional tracks, or absolute normalized rectangles for full control. A cell's fit mode controls how a source is scaled into its tile — contain to letterbox, cover to crop and fill, or fill to stretch."
msgstr "A layout decides where every tile sits on the canvas. Use a factory preset (such as 2x2 or 1+5), a CSS-grid with named areas and fractional tracks, or absolute normalized rectangles for full control. A cell's fit mode controls how a source is scaled into its tile — contain to letterbox, cover to crop and fill, or fill to stretch."

#: src/layout/components/validationMessages.tsx:19
msgid "A layout name is required."
msgstr "A layout name is required."

#: src/pages/SourcesPage.tsx:375
msgid "A location/title drawn on the face. Leave blank for none."
msgstr "A location/title drawn on the face. Leave blank for none."

#: src/pages/docs/DevicesHelpPage.tsx:33
msgid "A managed device is a piece of hardware Multiview supervises: a hardware decoder feeding a TV, a display node driving a video wall, or a cast target. The device entry you adopt is desired state — driver, management address, mode, credentials — and a supervised driver continuously converges the real device onto it: it probes, reconnects, re-applies the mode, and reports status."
msgstr "A managed device is a piece of hardware Multiview supervises: a hardware decoder feeding a TV, a display node driving a video wall, or a cast target. The device entry you adopt is desired state — driver, management address, mode, credentials — and a supervised driver continuously converges the real device onto it: it probes, reconnects, re-applies the mode, and reports status."

#: src/pages/DevicesPage.tsx:669
msgid "A managed device is declarative desired state: adopting starts a supervised driver that probes and converges it."
msgstr "A managed device is declarative desired state: adopting starts a supervised driver that probes and converges it."

#: src/pages/docs/FeaturesPage.tsx:151
msgid "A media player is a pre-declared channel that rolls a clip or still with VT (video-tape) transport: load an asset, cue to its in-point, play, pause, stop, and seek. For openers and loops it can vamp — loop a fill segment to hold until a cue — and then exit cleanly at the next loop boundary: arm the exit to leave after the current lap finishes, take it to leave at the soonest boundary, or cancel a pending exit to keep vamping. The transport panel shows each player's live state and playhead."
msgstr "A media player is a pre-declared channel that rolls a clip or still with VT (video-tape) transport: load an asset, cue to its in-point, play, pause, stop, and seek. For openers and loops it can vamp — loop a fill segment to hold until a cue — and then exit cleanly at the next loop boundary: arm the exit to leave after the current lap finishes, take it to leave at the soonest boundary, or cancel a pending exit to keep vamping. The transport panel shows each player's live state and playhead."

#: src/resources/FormControls.tsx:72
msgid "A mount point must start with /, e.g. /multiview."
msgstr "A mount point must start with /, e.g. /multiview."

#: src/pages/docs/ConfigPage.tsx:26
msgid "A Multiview deployment is one declarative document. It is authored as TOML and round-trips losslessly to JSON (the API wire form)."
msgstr "A Multiview deployment is one declarative document. It is authored as TOML and round-trips losslessly to JSON (the API wire form)."

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/CodecsPage.tsx:40
msgid "A multiviewer is inherently a transcoder: it must decode every source to composite them into one canvas, and then encode that canvas for its outputs. What it never does is transcode each tile separately — the cost would multiply by the number of tiles for no benefit."
msgstr "A multiviewer is inherently a transcoder: it must decode every source to composite them into one canvas, and then encode that canvas for its outputs. What it never does is transcode each tile separately — the cost would multiply by the number of tiles for no benefit."

#: src/pages/docs/ConfigPage.tsx:119
msgid "A named factory arrangement: <0>2x2</0>, <1>3x3</1>, <2>1+5</2>, or <3>pip</3>."
msgstr "A named factory arrangement: <0>2x2</0>, <1>3x3</1>, <2>1+5</2>, or <3>pip</3>."

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/GlossaryPage.tsx:316
msgid "A named set of display devices that should present together, with a per-member offset trim and a drift-alarm threshold. The group claims only its weakest member's sync tier, and the achieved tier is measured — never assumed. Cast devices can never be members."
msgstr "A named set of display devices that should present together, with a per-member offset trim and a drift-alarm threshold. The group claims only its weakest member's sync tier, and the achieved tier is measured — never assumed. Cast devices can never be members."

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/GlossaryPage.tsx:281
msgid "A named, atomically applied recall of multiview state: one salvo can switch the layout, rebind sources into cells, and update tally and labels in a single action. Borrowed from router control, where a salvo fires many crosspoint takes at once."
msgstr "A named, atomically applied recall of multiview state: one salvo can switch the layout, rebind sources into cells, and update tally and labels in a single action. Borrowed from router control, where a salvo fires many crosspoint takes at once."

#: src/pages/docs/DisplayNodesHelpPage.tsx:59
msgid "A node inherits the product's output doctrine: if its feed stops, it holds the last good frame, then shows its local slate — it never blanks mid-show because of a network blip, and the multiview program itself is never affected by a node's fate."
msgstr "A node inherits the product's output doctrine: if its feed stops, it holds the last good frame, then shows its local slate — it never blanks mid-show because of a network blip, and the multiview program itself is never affected by a node's fate."

#: src/pages/SupportPage.tsx:375
msgid "A paid plan adds an entitled support queue."
msgstr "A paid plan adds an entitled support queue."

#: src/pages/docs/ConfigPage.tsx:209
msgid "A per-cell <0>qos</0> block sets a degradation <1>priority</1> and strategy, so the engine sheds the cheapest tiles first under load before touching the program output."
msgstr "A per-cell <0>qos</0> block sets a degradation <1>priority</1> and strategy, so the engine sheds the cheapest tiles first under load before touching the program output."

#: src/pages/ProbesPage.tsx:487
msgid "A probe watches one cell for a fail state and raises an alarm after its dwell window."
msgstr "A probe watches one cell for a fail state and raises an alarm after its dwell window."

#: src/pages/WelcomePage.tsx:33
msgid "A quick first step: license this machine so it is ready to run."
msgstr "A quick first step: license this machine so it is ready to run."

#: src/pages/CastPage.tsx:101
msgid "A receiver address is required"
msgstr "A receiver address is required"

#: src/pages/DevicesPage.tsx:194
#: src/pages/SourcesPage.tsx:809
msgid "A reference only — never a plaintext secret. Leave blank for none."
msgstr "A reference only — never a plaintext secret. Leave blank for none."

#: src/resources/FormControls.tsx:49
msgid "A RIST URL must start with rist://."
msgstr "A RIST URL must start with rist://."

#: src/pages/SalvosPage.tsx:92
msgid "A salvo id is required"
msgstr "A salvo id is required"

#: src/pages/docs/FeaturesPage.tsx:139
msgid "A salvo is a named, atomically-applied recall. One salvo can switch the layout, rebind sources into cells, set tally colors, and update under-monitor display text — all at once — so an operator can move a whole arrangement (say, a VTR review setup) with a single action instead of a series of separate edits."
msgstr "A salvo is a named, atomically-applied recall. One salvo can switch the layout, rebind sources into cells, set tally colors, and update under-monitor display text — all at once — so an operator can move a whole arrangement (say, a VTR review setup) with a single action instead of a series of separate edits."

#: src/pages/MeshPage.tsx:74
msgid "A signed summary only — salted digests and a signed entitlement summary, never raw identity. The exhaustive list:"
msgstr "A signed summary only — salted digests and a signed entitlement summary, never raw identity. The exhaustive list:"

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/GlossaryPage.tsx:65
msgid "A small computer running Multiview's own playout software, driving one or more physical displays as a managed device. Enrolled by keypair identity, display nodes reach the frame-accurate sync tier — the class used for video walls."
msgstr "A small computer running Multiview's own playout software, driving one or more physical displays as a managed device. Enrolled by keypair identity, display nodes reach the frame-accurate sync tier — the class used for video walls."

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/GlossaryPage.tsx:126
msgid "A small receive-side buffer that absorbs the uneven arrival of network packets so frames can be consumed smoothly. Deeper buffers ride out worse networks but add latency. Each Multiview input has its own bounded buffering; an overflowing input drops its oldest data rather than growing without limit."
msgstr "A small receive-side buffer that absorbs the uneven arrival of network packets so frames can be consumed smoothly. Deeper buffers ride out worse networks but add latency. Each Multiview input has its own bounded buffering; an overflowing input drops its oldest data rather than growing without limit."

#: src/pages/docs/ComposePage.tsx:39
msgid "A small RTSP server that, on start, runs ffmpeg to publish a synthetic test pattern with a sine-wave audio tone to <0>rtsp://testsrc:8554/test</0>."
msgstr "A small RTSP server that, on start, runs ffmpeg to publish a synthetic test pattern with a sine-wave audio tone to <0>rtsp://testsrc:8554/test</0>."

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/CodecsPage.tsx:121
msgid "A software fallback always exists, so a build without any GPU still works — just with less headroom."
msgstr "A software fallback always exists, so a build without any GPU still works — just with less headroom."

#: src/pages/docs/FeaturesPage.tsx:40
msgid "A source is a managed input. Each one owns its ingest, decode, color handling, and reconnect behaviour, and is referenced by tiles via a stable id. Supported kinds include RTSP, HLS, MPEG-TS, SRT, RTMP, NDI, file, and a built-in synthetic test pattern. When a source stops delivering frames, its tile holds the last good frame and moves through a clear state machine — live, stale, reconnecting, no-signal — while the engine reconnects without disturbing the rest of the wall."
msgstr "A source is a managed input. Each one owns its ingest, decode, color handling, and reconnect behaviour, and is referenced by tiles via a stable id. Supported kinds include RTSP, HLS, MPEG-TS, SRT, RTMP, NDI, file, and a built-in synthetic test pattern. When a source stops delivering frames, its tile holds the last good frame and moves through a clear state machine — live, stale, reconnecting, no-signal — while the engine reconnects without disturbing the rest of the wall."

#: src/pages/SourcesPage.tsx:897
msgid "A source is an ingest input bound into the multiview by id."
msgstr "A source is an ingest input bound into the multiview by id."

#: src/pages/SyncGroupsPage.tsx:330
msgid "A sync group aligns its member devices' presentation; the achieved tier is measured, never assumed."
msgstr "A sync group aligns its member devices' presentation; the achieved tier is measured, never assumed."

#: src/pages/docs/SyncHelpPage.tsx:70
msgid "A sync group names the devices that should present together, with a per-member <0>offset_ms</0> trim (a fixed presentation delay for path-length differences) and a <1>target_skew_ms</1> drift threshold. The group claims the weakest member's tier — adding one vendor decoder to a wall of display nodes makes the whole group bounded-skew, and the UI says so rather than over-claiming. A member drifting past the target raises a warning alarm; \"Measure\" runs an on-demand skew measurement whose result arrives on the realtime stream."
msgstr "A sync group names the devices that should present together, with a per-member <0>offset_ms</0> trim (a fixed presentation delay for path-length differences) and a <1>target_skew_ms</1> drift threshold. The group claims the weakest member's tier — adding one vendor decoder to a wall of display nodes makes the whole group bounded-skew, and the UI says so rather than over-claiming. A member drifting past the target raises a warning alarm; \"Measure\" runs an on-demand skew measurement whose result arrives on the realtime stream."

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/GlossaryPage.tsx:258
msgid "A TCP push protocol that remains the most widely accepted way to send a live stream to a platform. Classic RTMP carries H.264 and AAC only; enhanced endpoints negotiate newer codecs. Latency is typically a few seconds."
msgstr "A TCP push protocol that remains the most widely accepted way to send a live stream to a platform. Classic RTMP carries H.264 and AAC only; enhanced endpoints negotiate newer codecs. Latency is typically a few seconds."

#: src/pages/docs/ComposePage.tsx:53
msgid "A tiny nginx that serves the HLS volume over HTTP so you can open the stream in a player at <0>http://[::1]:8888/multiview.m3u8</0>."
