#: src/pages/docs/concepts/GlossaryPage.tsx:173
msgid "Multicast Listener Discovery version 2 — the IPv6 protocol a receiver uses to tell the network which multicast groups (and, with source-specific multicast, which senders) it wants. It is the IPv6 successor to IPv4's IGMP and the primary group-join mechanism in Multiview's IPv6-first multicast support."
msgstr "Multicast Listener Discovery version 2 — the IPv6 protocol a receiver uses to tell the network which multicast groups (and, with source-specific multicast, which senders) it wants. It is the IPv6 successor to IPv4's IGMP and the primary group-join mechanism in Multiview's IPv6-first multicast support."

#: src/app/Sidebar.tsx:27
msgid "Multiview"
msgstr "Multiview"

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/CodecsPage.tsx:131
msgid "Multiview composites the canvas <0>once</0> per tick, encodes it <1>once per rendition</1>, and fans the same encoded packets out to every output that wants that rendition. Writing the wall to HLS while pushing it to an RTMP and an SRT destination at the same codec, resolution, and bitrate costs one encode — not three. A second encode is created only when an output genuinely needs a different codec, resolution, or bitrate."
msgstr "Multiview composites the canvas <0>once</0> per tick, encodes it <1>once per rendition</1>, and fans the same encoded packets out to every output that wants that rendition. Writing the wall to HLS while pushing it to an RTMP and an SRT destination at the same codec, resolution, and bitrate costs one encode — not three. A second encode is created only when an output genuinely needs a different codec, resolution, or bitrate."

#: src/pages/DevicesPage.tsx:74
msgid "Multiview display node (displaynode)"
msgstr "Multiview display node (displaynode)"

#: src/pages/docs/OverviewPage.tsx:35
msgid "Multiview is a hardware-accelerated live video multiview generator. It ingests many live sources, composites them into a templated grid on the GPU, and serves the combined picture as a continuous output stream. It is designed for monitoring walls and production multiviewers where the output must never stall."
msgstr "Multiview is a hardware-accelerated live video multiview generator. It ingests many live sources, composites them into a templated grid on the GPU, and serves the combined picture as a continuous output stream. It is designed for monitoring walls and production multiviewers where the output must never stall."

#: src/pages/DataPage.tsx:151
msgid "Multiview is source-available, so a source build can compile the heartbeat client out. We state that plainly: removing it does not grant a commercial right — the licence terms bind regardless of the binary. The official builds carry the heartbeat for the smooth claim and lease experience."
msgstr "Multiview is source-available, so a source build can compile the heartbeat client out. We state that plainly: removing it does not grant a commercial right — the licence terms bind regardless of the binary. The official builds carry the heartbeat for the smooth claim and lease experience."

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/LatencyPage.tsx:134
msgid "Multiview itself never trades the output cadence away: under load it degrades the cheapest tiles first and keeps the program output's timing intact."
msgstr "Multiview itself never trades the output cadence away: under load it degrades the cheapest tiles first and keeps the program output's timing intact."

#: src/pages/LayoutsPage.tsx:199
msgid "Multiview layouts. The accessible editor offers a form-based path equivalent to the drag-and-drop canvas. Apply is live on the running engine."
msgstr "Multiview layouts. The accessible editor offers a form-based path equivalent to the drag-and-drop canvas. Apply is live on the running engine."

#: src/pages/OutputsPage.tsx:225
msgid "Multiview Program"
msgstr "Multiview Program"

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/ColorPage.tsx:102
msgid "Multiview tone-maps HDR tiles into an SDR canvas (anchored so normal \"reference white\" content stays at a sensible brightness rather than scaling everything down), and only treats a stream as HDR when it is explicitly tagged as such — resolution alone never implies HDR. The canvas itself can also be configured as HDR (PQ or HLG) for monitoring HDR productions."
msgstr "Multiview tone-maps HDR tiles into an SDR canvas (anchored so normal \"reference white\" content stays at a sensible brightness rather than scaling everything down), and only treats a stream as HDR when it is explicitly tagged as such — resolution alone never implies HDR. The canvas itself can also be configured as HDR (PQ or HLG) for monitoring HDR productions."

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/TimingSyncPage.tsx:29
msgid "Multiview's output is paced by exactly one thing: a fixed-cadence internal clock. At every tick — for example every 1/50 s for a 50 fps canvas — it emits one finished frame, forever. Sources never set that pace. Each input writes its newest decoded frame into a per-tile store, and at each tick the compositor <0>samples</0> whatever is freshest there. A source that bursts, stalls, or dies changes only what its own tile shows — never when the next output frame goes out."
msgstr "Multiview's output is paced by exactly one thing: a fixed-cadence internal clock. At every tick — for example every 1/50 s for a 50 fps canvas — it emits one finished frame, forever. Sources never set that pace. Each input writes its newest decoded frame into a per-tile store, and at each tick the compositor <0>samples</0> whatever is freshest there. A source that bursts, stalls, or dies changes only what its own tile shows — never when the next output frame goes out."

#: src/pages/docs/DevicesHelpPage.tsx:113
msgid "Multiview's own display-node software for single-board computers and spare PCs driving displays; enrolled nodes are located by their keypair identity rather than an address, and present frame-accurate synchronized output."
msgstr "Multiview's own display-node software for single-board computers and spare PCs driving displays; enrolled nodes are located by their keypair identity rather than an address, and present frame-accurate synchronized output."

